data_path = 'drive/My Drive/mini_pro/data/DC/'

# List all files in the directory
files = os.listdir(data_path)

# Initialize an empty list to store the data from all files
data_11 = []

# Loop through each file
for file in files:
    # Check if the file name starts with 'deep-learning'
    if file.startswith(('deep-learning', 'neural-networks', 'reinforcement')):
        # Open the file
        with open(os.path.join(data_path, file)) as f:
            # Load the JSON data
            file_data = json.load(f)

            # Append the file_data to the data list
            data_11.append(file_data)


# You can process the data as needed
#for item in data_11:
    #print(item)

deep_learning_DC=json_normalize(data_11, record_path=['jobs_results'])

{'title': 'PhD position in Deep Neural Networks with Dempster Shafer Theory', 'company_name': "Universit d'Artois / LGI2A", 'location': '  Bethune, SC   ', 'via': 'via Glassdoor', 'description': "PhD position in Deep Neural Networks with Dempster Shafer Theory\n\nResearch Area...\n\nDeep Neural Networks, Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, Belief Functions, Dempster-Shafer\nTheory\n\nDescription\n\nWe are seeking a highly motivated and talented PhD student to join our research team at University of\nArtois - LGI2A - Decision and Information Fusion theme (DFI) - Bthune - France -\n(https://www.lgi2a.univ-artois.fr/spip/en/) focused on advancing the state-of-the-art in deep neural networks using Dempster Shafer theory of evidence. The successful candidate will have the opportunity to work on cutting-edge research projects and collaborate with other researchers in the field.\n\nSubject\n\nDeep neural networks (DNNs) refer to predictive models that exploit multiple layers of artificial neurons to compute a prediction [1,4]. In the original version, the layers are sequential and each neuron in a layer is connected with neurons in the previous layer. Many other alternative architectures have been proposed to adapt DNNs to solve specific and complex problems.\n\nOn the other hand, a theory called Dempster-Shafer theory of belief functions, or theory of evidence\n[15], has emerged as a rich and flexible generalization of the Bayesian probability theory, able to deal with imperfect (uncertain, imprecise, ) information. It is notably used in a growing number of applications such as classification (e.g. [2]), clustering (e.g. [3,7]) or information fusion (e.g. [5,13]).\n\nRecent works [6,16,17] have shown the interest of enriching a DNN with an additional distance-based\nDempster Shafer layer [2] for predicting belief functions. These belief functions can be of great interest to represent a reality as faithfully as possible, for example to perform a partial classification [8], i.e. decisions in favor of a group of classes.\n\nThe main idea of this thesis is to develop such deep evidential networks in more depth by exploiting methods developed at LGI2A allowing one to consider finer knowledge about the quality [12, 14] and the dependence of information [11], or the ignorance in predictions [9,10].\n\nTwo applications are envisaged: Image analysis from drones and fish population analysis.\n\nReferences\n\n[1] C. Experience with deep learning methods and their applications to biology.\n ML Ops experience: model tracking and governance, multiple models in different production contexts, etc.\n\nDesirable for the role\n A research program demonstrated by journal and conference publications in prestigious venues (with at least 1 publication as a leading author). data_path = 'drive/My Drive/mini_pro/data/USA/'

# List all files in the directory
files = os.listdir(data_path)

# Initialize an empty list to store the data from all files
data_12 = []

# Loop through each file
for file in files:
    # Check if the file name starts with 'deep-learning'
    if file.startswith(('deep-learning','neural-networks', 'reinforcement')):
        # Open the file
        with open(os.path.join(data_path, file)) as f:
            # Load the JSON data
            file_data = json.load(f)

            # Append the file_data to the data list
            data_12.append(file_data)

# You can process the data as needed
#for item in data_12:
    #print(item)

deep_learning_USA=json_normalize(data_12, record_path=['jobs_results'])

{'title': 'PhD position in Deep Neural Networks with Dempster Shafer Theory', 'company_name': "Universit d'Artois / LGI2A", 'location': '  Bethune, SC   ', 'via': 'via Glassdoor', 'description': "PhD position in Deep Neural Networks with Dempster Shafer Theory\n\nResearch Area...\n\nDeep Neural Networks, Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, Belief Functions, Dempster-Shafer\nTheory\n\nDescription\n\nWe are seeking a highly motivated and talented PhD student to join our research team at University of\nArtois - LGI2A - Decision and Information Fusion theme (DFI) - Bthune - France -\n(https://www.lgi2a.univ-artois.fr/spip/en/) focused on advancing the state-of-the-art in deep neural networks using Dempster Shafer theory of evidence. The successful candidate will have the opportunity to work on cutting-edge research projects and collaborate with other researchers in the field.\n\nSubject\n\nDeep neural networks (DNNs) refer to predictive models that exploit multiple layers of artificial neurons to compute a prediction [1,4]. In the original version, the layers are sequential and each neuron in a layer is connected with neurons in the previous layer. Many other alternative architectures have been proposed to adapt DNNs to solve specific and complex problems.\n\nOn the other hand, a theory called Dempster-Shafer theory of belief functions, or theory of evidence\n[15], has emerged as a rich and flexible generalization of the Bayesian probability theory, able to deal with imperfect (uncertain, imprecise, ) information. It is notably used in a growing number of applications such as classification (e.g. [2]), clustering (e.g. [3,7]) or information fusion (e.g. [5,13]).\n\nRecent works [6,16,17] have shown the interest of enriching a DNN with an additional distance-based\nDempster Shafer layer [2] for predicting belief functions. These belief functions can be of great interest to represent a reality as faithfully as possible, for example to perform a partial classification [8], i.e. decisions in favor of a group of classes.\n\nThe main idea of this thesis is to develop such deep evidential networks in more depth by exploiting methods developed at LGI2A allowing one to consider finer knowledge about the quality [12, 14] and the dependence of information [11], or the ignorance in predictions [9,10].\n\nTwo applications are envisaged: Image analysis from drones and fish population analysis.\n\nReferences\n\n[1] C. M. Bishop. Pattern recognition and machine learning, 5th Edition. Information science and statistics. Springer, 2007.\n\n[2] T. Denoeux. A neural network classifier based on dempster-shafer theory. Information Science,\n528:1745, 2020.\n\n[4] I. Goodfellow, Y. Bengio and A. Courville: Deep Learning (Adaptive Computation and Machine\nLearning), MIT Press, Cambridge (USA), 2016.\n\n[5] L. Lymphoma segmentation from 3D PET-CT images using a deep evidential network. International Journal of Approximate Reasoning, Volume 149, pages\n39-60, 2022.\n\n[7] F. Li, S. Li, and T. Denux. Combining clusterings in the belief function framework. Array, 6:100018,\n2020.\n\n[8] L. Ma and T. Denux. Partial classification in the belief function framework. Knowledge-Based\nSystems, 214: article 106742, 2021.\n\n[9] P. Minary, F. Pichon, D. Mercier, E. Lefvre and B. Droit. In [8]:
def clean_text(text):
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[^(a-zA-Z)\s]','', text)
    text= re.sub('\[[^]]*\]', '', text)    
    return text

DL_des['description']=DL_des['description'].apply(clean_text)

DL_des['description'] = DL_des['description'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x.split() if word not in (stpwrd)]))

    ngram_range = (1,3),
    max_features=1000
)

cv.fit(DL_des['description'])

In [16]:
documentAssembler = DocumentAssembler().setInputCol("description").setOutputCol("document")
 
tokenizer = Tokenizer().setInputCols(["document"]).setOutputCol("token")
 
# normalizer defaults to changing all words to lowercase, so setLowercase(False) to maintain input case.
normalizer = (
    Normalizer().setInputCols(["token"]).setOutputCol("normalized").setLowercase(True)
)
 
stop_words = (
    StopWordsCleaner.pretrained("stopwords_en", "en")
    .setInputCols(["normalized"])
    .setOutputCol("clean_normalized")
    .setCaseSensitive(False)
)
 
stemmer = Stemmer().setInputCols(["clean_normalized"]).setOutputCol("stem")
 
 
# finisher converts tokens to human-readable output
finisher = Finisher().setInputCols(["stem"]).setCleanAnnotations(False)
 
pipeline = Pipeline().setStages(
    [
        documentAssembler,
        tokenizer,
        normalizer,
        stop_words,
        stemmer,
        finisher,
    ]
)

In [28]:
def convert_to_network(df):
    print(df)
 
    #BUILD GRAPH
    G = nx.DiGraph()  # DIRECTED
    for row in df.iterrows():
        # for column in df.columns:
        lhs="_".join(row[1][0])
        rhs="_".join(row[1][1])
        sup=row[1][8]; #print(conviction)
        if(lhs not in G.nodes): 
            G.add_node(lhs)
        if(rhs not in G.nodes): 
            G.add_node(rhs)
 
        edge=(lhs,rhs)
        if edge not in G.edges:
            G.add_edge(lhs, rhs, weight=sup)
 
    # print(G.nodes)
    # print(G.edges)
    return G
In [35]:
def plot_network(G):
    #SPECIFIY X-Y POSITIONS FOR PLOTTING
    pos=nx.random_layout(G)
 
    #GENERATE PLOT
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    fig.set_size_inches(15, 15)
 
    #assign colors based on attributes
    weights_e     = [G[u][v]['weight'] for u,v in G.edges()]
 
    #SAMPLE CMAP FOR COLORS 
    cmap=plt.cm.get_cmap('Blues')
    colors_e     = [cmap(G[u][v]['weight']*10) for u,v in G.edges()]
 
    #PLOT
    nx.draw(
    G,
    edgecolors="white",
    edge_color='#D4EFDF',
    node_size=2500,
    linewidths=0.1,
    font_size=9,
    font_color="black",
    #font_weight="bold",
    width=weights_e,
    with_labels=True,
    pos=pos,
    ax=ax,
    node_color = "#B2E2F7"
    )
 
    ax.set_title('Network of Job Description in Neural Network Deep Learning and Reinforcement Learning Field', fontsize=20)
    #plt.show()
